\toc1 The Epistle of Paul to Philemon
\mt1 The Epistle of Paul to
\mt2 PHILEMON
\c 1
\s1 Greeting
\m 
\v 1 \w Paul|strong="G3972"\w*, \w a|strong="G2532"\w* \w prisoner|strong="G1198"\w* \w for|strong="G2532"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w Christ|strong="G5547"\w*,\f + \fr 1:1 \ft Since Paul elsewhere calls himself a slave of Jesus, he would also be a prisoner of Jesus, but in this context I understand him to be saying that he is in prison because of Jesus.\f* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* brother \w Timothy|strong="G5095"\w*, \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* beloved \w Philemon|strong="G5371"\w*, \w our|strong="G2424"\w* \w fellow|strong="G4904"\w* \w worker|strong="G4904"\w*,
\v 2 \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* beloved\f + \fr 1:2 \ft Instead of “beloved”, some 5% of the Greek manuscripts have ‘sister’ (as in NIV, NASB, LB, TEV, etc.). In any case, Apphia is a woman.\f* Apphia \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w our|strong="G2532"\w* \w fellow|strong="G4961"\w* \w soldier|strong="G4961"\w* Archippus, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w congregation|strong="G1577"\w* \w at|strong="G2596"\w* \w your|strong="G2532"\w* (sg)\f + \fr 1:2 \ft Since English is ambiguous as to whether the second person personal pronoun is singular or plural, and since Paul mixes both in this letter, it becomes necessary to let the reader know which is which. The congregation met in Philemon's house.\f* \w house|strong="G3624"\w*:
\v 3 \w Grace|strong="G5485"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* (pl) \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w peace|strong="G1515"\w* \w from|strong="G1515"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w* \w our|strong="G2316"\w* \w Father|strong="G3962"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* Sovereign \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w Christ|strong="G5547"\w*.
\s1 Paul commends Philemon
\p 
\v 4 \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w always|strong="G3842"\w* \w thank|strong="G2168"\w* \w my|strong="G2168"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w* \w as|strong="G1909"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w make|strong="G4160"\w* \w mention|strong="G3417"\w* \w of|strong="G2316"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w* (sg) \w in|strong="G1909"\w* \w my|strong="G2168"\w* \w prayers|strong="G4335"\w*,
\v 5 hearing \w of|strong="G2532"\w* \w your|strong="G2962"\w* love \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w faith|strong="G4102"\w* \w that|strong="G3739"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w* \w have|strong="G2192"\w* \w toward|strong="G1519"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w Lord|strong="G2962"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w*, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w for|strong="G1519"\w* \w all|strong="G3956"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* saints,
\v 6 \w so|strong="G1519"\w* \w that|strong="G3588"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w sharing|strong="G2842"\w* \w of|strong="G1722"\w* \w your|strong="G3956"\w* (sg) \w faith|strong="G4102"\w* \w may|strong="G5547"\w* \w become|strong="G1096"\w* \w powerful|strong="G1756"\w* \w through|strong="G1722"\w* \w a|strong="G1096"\w* \w full|strong="G3956"\w* understanding \w of|strong="G1722"\w* \w every|strong="G3956"\w* \w good|strong="G3956"\w* \w thing|strong="G3956"\w* \w that|strong="G3588"\w* \w is|strong="G3588"\w* \w among|strong="G1722"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w* (pl) \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w are|strong="G3588"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w Christ|strong="G5547"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G1096"\w*;\f + \fr 1:6 \ft Verse 6 probably reads quite differently in your version of the Bible. Were you aware that the “your” refers to Philemon while the “you” refers to the congregation? [The MSS evidence is about evenly divided between “you” and ‘us’, but I follow the best line of transmission, as in AV and NKJV.] The verse usually ends with “you/us in Christ Jesus”, but the preposition is properly “into”, which does not make for smooth English. The reference is to those who have believed \nd into\nd* Jesus (as He Himself invariably said)—they were outside but have moved inside. So Paul is referring to a group of regenerated people and to the aggregate of ‘good things’ to be found among them; which I assume would certainly include the gifts of the Spirit, as well as His fruit. As Philemon's understanding of these resources increases, the sharing of his faith will become more powerful, and for this Paul prays. At the end of the verse, perhaps 2% of the Greek manuscripts, of objectively inferior quality, omit “Jesus” (as in NIV, NASB, LB, TEV, etc.).\f*
\v 7 \w yes|strong="G1063"\w*, \w we|strong="G3754"\w* \w have|strong="G2192"\w* \w much|strong="G4183"\w* thanksgiving\f + \fr 1:7 \ft Instead of “thanksgiving”, some 12% of the Greek manuscripts have ‘joy’, as in most versions.\f* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w encouragement|strong="G3874"\w* \w because|strong="G3754"\w* \w of|strong="G1223"\w* \w your|strong="G1223"\w* (sg) love, \w in|strong="G1909"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w hearts|strong="G4698"\w* \w of|strong="G1223"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* saints \w have|strong="G2192"\w* \w been|strong="G2192"\w* refreshed \w through|strong="G1223"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w*, brother.
\s1 Paul intercedes for Onesimus
\p 
\v 8 \w Now|strong="G1722"\w* \w then|strong="G1352"\w*, \w though|strong="G1722"\w* \w I|strong="G1352"\w* \w have|strong="G2192"\w* \w all|strong="G1722"\w* \w boldness|strong="G3954"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w Christ|strong="G5547"\w* \w to|strong="G1722"\w* \w order|strong="G2004"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w* (sg) \w to|strong="G1722"\w* \w do|strong="G2192"\w* \w what|strong="G3588"\w* \w is|strong="G3588"\w* right,\f + \fr 1:8 \ft Paul starts out by asserting his authority, but softens it with an emotional appeal, appealing to Philemon's emotions in various ways.\f*
\v 9 \w I|strong="G2532"\w*—\w being|strong="G1510"\w* none \w other|strong="G1161"\w* \w than|strong="G2532"\w* \w Paul|strong="G3972"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w old|strong="G2532"\w* \w man|strong="G5108"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w now|strong="G1161"\w* \w also|strong="G2532"\w* \w a|strong="G5613"\w* \w prisoner|strong="G1198"\w* \w for|strong="G1223"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* \w Christ|strong="G5547"\w*—\w would|strong="G2532"\w* \w rather|strong="G3123"\w* \w appeal|strong="G3870"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w you|strong="G1510"\w*, \w for|strong="G1223"\w* love's \w sake|strong="G1223"\w*.
\v 10 \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w appeal|strong="G3870"\w* \w to|strong="G1722"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w* \w on|strong="G1722"\w* \w behalf|strong="G4012"\w* \w of|strong="G4012"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w son|strong="G5043"\w* \w whom|strong="G3739"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* begot \w while|strong="G1722"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w my|strong="G1699"\w* \w chains|strong="G1199"\w*, \w Onesimus|strong="G3682"\w*,\f + \fr 1:10 \ft When not a proper name, the word is an adjective meaning ‘useful’.\f* \w whom|strong="G3739"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w am|strong="G1473"\w* sending back
\v 11 —\w formerly|strong="G4218"\w* \w he|strong="G2532"\w* \w was|strong="G3588"\w* unprofitable \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w*, \w but|strong="G1161"\w* \w now|strong="G1161"\w* \w he|strong="G2532"\w* \w is|strong="G3588"\w* \w profitable|strong="G2173"\w*, \w both|strong="G2532"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w*.
\p 
\v 12 \w So|strong="G3778"\w* receive\f + \fr 1:12 \ft Some 1.5% of the Greek manuscripts, of objectively inferior quality, omit “receive”, as in NIV, NASB, LB, TEV, etc., which obliges them to adjust their rendering accordingly.\f* \w him|strong="G3588"\w*, \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w my|strong="G1699"\w* \w very|strong="G3778"\w* \w heart|strong="G4698"\w*
\v 13 —\w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w would|strong="G1014"\w* \w have|strong="G1473"\w* liked \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w keep|strong="G2722"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w* \w with|strong="G1722"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w*, \w so|strong="G2443"\w* \w that|strong="G2443"\w* \w he|strong="G3739"\w* \w might|strong="G2098"\w* \w minister|strong="G1247"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w your|strong="G1722"\w* \w place|strong="G1722"\w*, \w while|strong="G1722"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w am|strong="G1473"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w chains|strong="G1199"\w* \w for|strong="G5228"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Gospel|strong="G2098"\w*,
\v 14 \w but|strong="G1161"\w* \w I|strong="G1161"\w* \w did|strong="G4160"\w* \w not|strong="G3361"\w* \w want|strong="G2309"\w* \w to|strong="G2443"\w* \w do|strong="G4160"\w* \w anything|strong="G3762"\w* \w without|strong="G5565"\w* \w your|strong="G4674"\w* \w consent|strong="G1106"\w*, \w so|strong="G2443"\w* \w that|strong="G2443"\w* \w your|strong="G4674"\w* contribution might \w be|strong="G1510"\w* \w voluntary|strong="G2309"\w*, \w not|strong="G3361"\w* \w as|strong="G5613"\w* \w an|strong="G1510"\w* imposition.
\v 15 \w Perhaps|strong="G5029"\w* \w this|strong="G3778"\w* \w is|strong="G3778"\w* \w why|strong="G1223"\w* \w he|strong="G3778"\w* \w was|strong="G3778"\w* removed\f + \fr 1:15 \ft “Removed” is passive; Paul implies that God was behind the flight of Onesimus.\f* \w for|strong="G1063"\w* \w a|strong="G4314"\w* \w while|strong="G5610"\w*, \w so|strong="G2443"\w* \w that|strong="G2443"\w* \w you|strong="G3778"\w* would \w have|strong="G3778"\w* \w him|strong="G4314"\w* \w forever|strong="G1223"\w*
\v 16 —\w no|strong="G3756"\w* \w longer|strong="G2089"\w* \w as|strong="G5613"\w* \w a|strong="G5613"\w* \w slave|strong="G1401"\w*, \w but|strong="G1161"\w* \w more|strong="G3123"\w* \w than|strong="G5228"\w* \w a|strong="G5613"\w* \w slave|strong="G1401"\w*, \w a|strong="G5613"\w* beloved brother, \w very|strong="G2532"\w* \w much|strong="G4214"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w* \w but|strong="G1161"\w* \w even|strong="G2532"\w* \w more|strong="G3123"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w*, \w both|strong="G2532"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w flesh|strong="G4561"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Lord|strong="G2962"\w*.\f + \fr 1:16 \ft What does “both in flesh and in the Lord” mean? Onesimus is now a brother in the Lord, but was he also Philemon's physical brother? But if a brother, how did he become his slave? I don't know. If I had to guess I would imagine that Philemon's father begot Onesimus of a slave woman. Whatever the messy consequences of people's lives without Christ, this letter illustrates nicely how the Gospel can straighten things out.\f*
\s1 Paul asks for obedience
\p 
\v 17 \w So|strong="G3767"\w* \w if|strong="G1487"\w* \w you|strong="G1487"\w* \w consider|strong="G2192"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w* \w a|strong="G2192"\w* \w partner|strong="G2844"\w*, \w receive|strong="G4355"\w* \w him|strong="G4355"\w* \w as|strong="G5613"\w* \w if|strong="G1487"\w* \w it|strong="G1487"\w* \w were|strong="G5613"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w*.\f + \fr 1:17 \ft Verses 17-19 are often used as an illustration of substitutionary atonement, wherein Philemon would represent the Father, Paul the Son, and Onesimus the sinner—what Onesimus owes is charged to Paul, so Onesimus can go free. (Of course the second half of verse 19 doesn't fit; the Father doesn't owe His life to the Son.)\f*
\v 18 \w If|strong="G1487"\w* \w he|strong="G1161"\w* wronged \w you|strong="G4771"\w* \w or|strong="G2228"\w* \w owes|strong="G3784"\w* \w anything|strong="G5100"\w*, \w charge|strong="G1677"\w* \w it|strong="G1161"\w* \w to|strong="G5100"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w*.
\v 19 \w I|strong="G1473"\w*, \w Paul|strong="G3972"\w*, \w am|strong="G1473"\w* \w writing|strong="G1125"\w* \w with|strong="G2532"\w* \w my|strong="G1699"\w* \w own|strong="G1699"\w* \w hand|strong="G5495"\w*, “\w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w will|strong="G2532"\w* repay” (rather \w than|strong="G2532"\w* \w say|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2443"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w* \w actually|strong="G2532"\w* \w owe|strong="G4359"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w* \w your|strong="G2532"\w* \w very|strong="G2532"\w* \w self|strong="G4572"\w*!).\f + \fr 1:19 \ft Dear me, Paul builds such a strong case that there is really no way that Philemon can refuse!\f*
\v 20 \w Yes|strong="G3483"\w* brother, \w let|strong="G3685"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w* \w have|strong="G1473"\w* \it this\it* \w benefit|strong="G3685"\w* \w from|strong="G3588"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Lord|strong="G2962"\w*; refresh \w my|strong="G1722"\w* \w heart|strong="G4698"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Lord|strong="G2962"\w*.\f + \fr 1:20 \ft Instead of “the Lord”, some 20% of the Greek manuscripts have ‘Christ’ (as in NIV, NASB, LB, TEV, etc.).\f*
\p 
\v 21 \w Being|strong="G2532"\w* \w confident|strong="G3982"\w* \w of|strong="G2532"\w* \w your|strong="G2532"\w* \w obedience|strong="G5218"\w*, \w I|strong="G3739"\w* \w write|strong="G1125"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w*, \w knowing|strong="G1492"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w* (sg) \w will|strong="G2532"\w* \w do|strong="G4160"\w* \w even|strong="G2532"\w* \w more|strong="G5228"\w* \w than|strong="G5228"\w* \w I|strong="G3739"\w* \w say|strong="G3004"\w*.
\v 22 \w But|strong="G1161"\w* \w meanwhile|strong="G1161"\w*, \w do|strong="G2532"\w* \w prepare|strong="G2090"\w* \w a|strong="G2532"\w* guest room \w for|strong="G1063"\w* \w me|strong="G1473"\w*, \w because|strong="G3754"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w hope|strong="G1679"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w through|strong="G1223"\w* \w your|strong="G1223"\w* (pl) \w prayers|strong="G4335"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w will|strong="G2532"\w* \w be|strong="G2532"\w* \w graciously|strong="G5483"\w* \w bestowed|strong="G5483"\w* \w on|strong="G1161"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* (pl).\f + \fr 1:22 \ft Might verse 22 be a veiled threat, that Paul could show up to check up on Philemon? Note that Paul implies that his physical presence will be a blessing.\f*
\s1 Farewell
\p 
\v 23 \w Epaphras|strong="G1889"\w*, \w my|strong="G1722"\w* \w fellow|strong="G4869"\w* \w prisoner|strong="G4869"\w* \w for|strong="G1722"\w* \w Christ|strong="G5547"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w*, greets \w you|strong="G4771"\w* (sg),
\v 24 \w as|strong="G1473"\w* \w do|strong="G3588"\w* \w Mark|strong="G3138"\w*, Aristarchus, \w Demas|strong="G1214"\w* \w and|strong="G3588"\w* \w Luke|strong="G3065"\w*, \w my|strong="G1473"\w* \w fellow|strong="G4904"\w* \w workers|strong="G4904"\w*.\f + \fr 1:24 \ft Evidently Epaphras was also in prison, but not the others. If Mark was there as a result of the request in 2 Timothy 4:11, then this letter was written some time later.\f*
\p 
\v 25 \w The|strong="G3588"\w* \w grace|strong="G5485"\w* \w of|strong="G4151"\w* \w our|strong="G2424"\w* \w Lord|strong="G2962"\w* \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w*\f + \fr 1:25 \ft I follow the best line of transmission (albeit representing only some 20% of the Greek manuscripts here) in not adding ‘Christ’. Being a very personal letter, Paul is less formal.\f* \w be|strong="G3588"\w* \w with|strong="G3326"\w* \w your|strong="G2962"\w* (pl) \w spirit|strong="G4151"\w*.\f + \fr 1:25 \ft Since ‘spirit’ is singular, is it that of the congregation?—or does Paul mean the spirit of each one of the individuals? Even though regenerated we still need grace, and a congregation certainly needs it.\f* Amen. 
